    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Motif comprising a trefoil flower resembling an upright stylized ivy leaf, a common ornament in English Late Gothic and Tudor architecture, especially for brattishing. For the circular red and white double rose motif implemented by Henry VII, use "Tudor rose."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000032401/Fleming et al., Penguin Dictionary of Architecture (1981)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000105490/Merriam-Webster Dictionary [online] (2008-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Motivo ornamental semejante a una hoja de hiedra erguida, común en el Gótico Tardío inglés y arquitectura Tudor, sobre todo para la crestería.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Decoratieve motieven gelijk aan een rechtopstaand gestileerd klimopblad, gebruikelijk in Engeland in de eerste helft van de 16e eeuw.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
